							</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

			<div class="comment-content">
				<p>The big concern with this set of incentives is crisis instability.  A PRC regime that thought it faced a regime-threatening crisis may decide that the risks of an attack were less than the risks of inaction.  Contrast it with other scenarios where conventional deterrence succeeded, and scenarios where it failed and one party initiated war by surprise attack.  This looks worrisomely like a scenario which is ripe for failure of deterrence.  USA maintaining ambiguity about its commitment to Taiwan is probably not stability enhancing.</p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content -->

		</article><!-- .comment-body -->

