		<div id="comment-2631" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
		<article id="div-comment-2631" class="comment-body">
			<footer class="comment-meta">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
					<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/db98a77e018115589ae2134617604489?s=32&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/db98a77e018115589ae2134617604489?s=64&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' loading='lazy'/><b class="fn">Tim</b>				</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				<div class="comment-metadata">
					<a href="https://scholars-stage.org/fear-the-logic-of-the-first-strike/#comment-2631">
												<time datetime="2021-07-05T17:06:40+00:00" title="05 July, 2021 at 5:06 pm">
							05 July, 2021 at 5:06 pm						</time>
					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

							</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

			<div class="comment-content">
				<p>&#8216;Taiwan contingency&#8217; will be more of an extended land campaign than a naval warfare for the Chinese.  The strait is too narrow to preclude PLA airborne assaults and precision long range artillery, and too shallow to wage effective submarine warfare against PLA invasion.  With Marine&#8217;s FD2030 blue print, (given up armor, amphib, helo-lift, and air power) it&#8217;s an indication the 1st chain around Taiwan is on a trip-wire defense footing.  Furthermore, unless Marines deploys its missiles on Taiwan itself (where there is room to roam), I don&#8217;t see where/how Marines can &#8216;shoot &amp; scoot&#8217; their HIMAR batteries to escape Chinese pre-emptive (and counter battery) strikes on tiny islands north and south of Taiwan.</p>
<p>Strategically, if push comes to shove (between the US and China), I foresee China first will attempt to grab Taiwan, and forces the US to either wage air-sea-battle(s) 100 miles off the Chinese coast, or wage a long (maybe decades long) offshore campaign away from the severed 1st chain.  The latter is probably more probable than the former.</p>
			</div><!-- .comment-content -->

		</article><!-- .comment-body -->

